{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":9788,"record_hash":"sha256:434f1aac7f56c4746696c9457b88afe8d644969ba4c8ea21deb1b98a2dbc53ee","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:30:48.768Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: a70d56\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1937\nOutput:\n# Agent Session Handoff Design\n\nThis note sketches the handoff feature that sits above the `but-agentlog`\nprimitives. It is intentionally not an implementation contract yet.\n\n## Goal\n\nLet a developer continue work from one machine, agent, or provider session in\nanother machine, agent, or provider session.\n\nThe target experience:\n\n1. work happens on a branch with agentlog capture enabled\n2. GitMeta sync moves captured agentlog data with the repository metadata\n3. another machine checks out or switches to the branch\n4. the user asks an agent to catch up\n5. the agent uses GitButler commands to discover and read relevant prior session\n   context\n6. the new agent continues with enough context to be useful, without pretending\n   it has natively resumed the old provider session\n\nThis is contextual handoff, not exact provider-native replay.\n\n## Current Building Blocks\n\nThe primitive layer can already provide the facts a handoff flow needs:\n\n- durable project-scoped sessions\n- capture turns within sessions\n- ordered transcript records within each turn\n- environment observations for each turn\n- GitMeta sync of the stored data\n- verified lookup of sessions related to a branch, review, or change\n- bounded hydration of related turn windows\n\nThat is enough to design an agent-facing workflow without adding product-shaped\nstate to `but-agentlog`.\n\n## Design Bias\n\nThe agent should get tools, not a generated handoff essay.\n\nThat said, raw transcript access alone is not enough. Once sessions include\nsubagents, compactions, large backfills, and repeated captures, asking the next\nagent to infer everything from a giant transcript is brittle and expensive.\n\nThe useful middle ground is:\n\n- deterministic orientation commands\n- bounded transcript hydration\n- stable machine-readable JSON\n- enough metadata to let the agent choose what to read next\n- optional human-readable output for manual debugging\n\nDo not bake a model-generated\n[TRUNCATED]\ner should not hide these. It should make them legible:\n\n- main-looking sessions: long-running, many incremental turns, latest user asks\n- sidecar-looking sessions: one backfill, review prompt, separate provider\n  session id, often created close together\n- compacted/resumed sessions: may have a new provider session id but overlapping\n  prior conversation context\n\nAvoid hard-coding those labels until the source data supports them. For now,\nexpose enough facts for the consuming agent to decide.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- no provider-native resume\n- no generated persistent handoff summary\n- no durable inferred ownership like \"this branch belongs to this session\"\n- no GitButler app API dependency for the first flow\n- no automatic transcript dumping into `but status`\n- no product-specific review browsing payloads\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- Should the CLI expose one ergonomic `handoff` command, or keep only generic\n  primitives and let a skill orchestrate them?\n- Do we need a first-class \"session outline\" primitive in `but-agentlog`, or can\n  it be assembled cheaply from existing reads?\n- Can we reliably capture provider metadata that distinguishes top-level\n  sessions from spawned subagents?\n- Should compaction/resume grouping be a later derived feature, or do we need to\n  store more source metadata now to make it possible?\n- How much transcript text should human-readable output show by default?\n\n## Recommended First Implementation Slice\n\nDo not implement \"handoff\" as one magic command yet.\n\nFirst add enough generic CLI read commands that an agent or skill can perform\nhandoff:\n\n1. enhance `agentlog sessions` so JSON includes session outline fields, not just\n   keys\n2. add a bounded timeline command for one session\n3. add a related-detail command that hydrates records around highlighted turns\n4. write a small skill/workflow note that tells agents how to use those commands\n\nThat keeps the feature honest. If the workflow feels clumsy after using the\nprimitives on real branches, then add a convenience `handoff` command above\nthem.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:30:48.768Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}